    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-11-28T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-11-28T17:00:00-05:00" n="806"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d806">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">839.00/11–2845: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in the Dominican Republic</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Scherer</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-11-28T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 28, 1945—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>351. Urtel 455, Nov. 19, 3 p.m. As suggested by you please address identical
                    letters to the sugar companies concerned setting forth in the strongest terms
                    Depts position that any American businessman or company engaging in political
                    activities (including the making of <pb facs="1005" n="991" xml:id="pg_991"/>
                    campaign contributions whether in the firm’s name or by an American citizen as
                    an individual) need expect no assistance from the Dept or from our diplomatic
                    missions abroad. You should make clear that in the opinion of this government
                    assistance of the type requested of the companies by Trujillo constitutes such
                    participation. You should refer in your letters to the restatement of this
                    policy by Assistant Secretary Braden in his speech before the National Foreign
                    Trade Convention at New York on November 14, a copy of which has been sent
                        you.<note n="31" xml:id="d806fn31">For text of speech, see Department of
                        State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, November 18, 1945, p. 798.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
